Visualizing the K-means Reduced Color Space¶

Incheol [CC BY-SA 4.0], via Wikimedia Commons

K-means Algorithm:

  1. Initialization: Randomly sample $k$ colors from the input image. These are the initial $k$ means $\mu_1,\mu_2,...,\mu_k$.
  1. For each pixel in the image, assign it to its nearest mean given by $$c^{(i)} := \textrm{argmin}_{j}\left \|x^{(i)} - \mu_j \right \|^2$$
  1. Update the means using the pixel assignments from Step 2. $$\mu_j := \frac{\sum_{i}^{n}1\left \{c^{(i)} = j \right \}x^{(i)}}{\sum_{i}^{n}1\left \{c^{(i)} = j \right \}}$$
  1. Repeat Steps 2 and 3 until convergence.

kmeans = MiniBatchKMeans(16).fit(img_data)
k_colors = kmeans.cluster_centers_[kmeans.predict(img_data)] # predicting the color data

y = plot_utils(img_data , colors = k_colors , title = "Reduced color space : 16 colors")
y.colorSpace()

adding interactive controls¶

In [11]:
# ipython has interactives like dropdown...

img_dir = 'images/'
In [12]:
# now define the function 
@interact # we add this decorator for the function to interact
def color_compression(image=os.listdir(img_dir) , k=IntSlider(min=1 , max = 250 , steps =1 , value =16 , continuous_update = False , layout = dict(width='100%'))):  # gives list of images in the directory 
    
    input_img = io.imread(img_dir+image)
    img_data = (input_img/255.0).reshape(-1,3)
    kmeans = MiniBatchKMeans(k).fit(img_data)
    k_colors = kmeans.cluster_centers_[kmeans.predict(img_data)]
    k_img = np.reshape(k_colors,(input_img.shape))
    
    fig,(ax1 , ax2) = plt.subplots(1,2) # 1 row 2 cols 
    fig.suptitle('K-Means Image Compression',fontsize = 20)
    
    ax1.set_title('Compressed')
    ax1.set_xticks([])
    ax1.set_yticks([])
    ax1.imshow(k_img)
    
    ax2.set_title('Original(16,777,216 colors)')
    ax2.set_xticks([])
    ax2.set_yticks([])
    ax2.imshow(input_img)
    
    # the titles would overlap
    
    plt.subplots_adjust(top=0.85)
    plt.show()
